TypeSignature.Value: .class public interface auto ansi abstract FillFormat

Docs.summary: Represents fill formatting for a shape. A shape can have a solid, gradient, texture, pattern, picture, or semi-transparent fill.

remarks.para: Use the Fill property of a , , or object to return a FillFormat object.
Many of the properties of the FillFormat object are read-only. To set one of these properties, you have to apply the corresponding method.

MemberSignature.Value: Public ReadOnly Property Creator As Integer
public: property int Creator { int get(); };

Docs.summary: Returns a 32-bit integer that indicates the application in which the specified object was created.

remarks.para: If the object was created in Microsoft Word, this property returns the hexadecimal number 4D535744, which represents the string "MSWD." This value can also be represented by the constant wdCreatorCode.

The Creator property was primarily designed to be used on the Macintosh, where each application has a four-character creator code. For example, Microsoft Word has the creator code MSWD. For additional information about this property, consult the language reference Help included with Microsoft Office Macintosh Edition.

MemberSignature.Value: public: property float GradientAngle { float get(); void set(float value); };

Docs.summary: Gets or sets the angle of the gradient fill for the specified fill format.
Docs.value: The angle of the gradient fill for the specified fill format.

remarks.para: Read/write. A gradient fill can be specified in the formatting for various elements (shapes) in a chart. For example, you can use the Format Data Series dialog box to format the columns in a Column chart to a gradient fill. In this case, this property corresponds to the setting of the Angle box in the Fill category of the Format Data Series dialog box. The valid range of values for this property is from zero through 359.9.

MemberSignature.Value: Public ReadOnly Property GradientDegree As Single
public: property float GradientDegree { float get(); };

Docs.summary: Returns a value that indicates how dark or light a one-color gradient fill is.

remarks.para: A value of 0 (zero) means that black is mixed in with the shape's foreground color to form the gradient; a value of 1 means that white is mixed in; and values between 0 and 1 mean that a darker or lighter shade of the foreground color is mixed in.
Use the method to set the gradient degree for the fill.

Docs.summary: Gets the collection associated with the specified fill format.
Docs.value: The collection associated with the specified fill format.

remarks.para: Read/write. Gradients are a smooth transition from one color state to another. The endpoints of these sections are called stops. You can use the HYPERLINK "ms-help://AstroNS2/WINWORD.DEV/content/ms-help/HV10343554.htm" GradientStops.Insert method to add gradient stops to the GradientStops collection for the specified object.

Docs.summary: Returns the gradient style for the specified fill.

remarks.para: Use the or method to set the gradient style for the fill.
Attempting to return this property for a fill that doesn't have a gradient generates an error. Use the property to determine whether the fill has a gradient.

MemberSignature.Value: Public ReadOnly Property GradientVariant As Integer
public: property int GradientVariant { int get(); };

Docs.summary: Returns the gradient variant for the specified fill as an integer value from 1 to 4 for most gradient fills.

remarks.para: If the gradient style is msoGradientFromCenter, this property returns either 1 or 2. The values for this property correspond to the gradient variants (numbered from left to right and from top to bottom) on the Gradient tab in the Fill Effects dialog box.
This property is read-only. Use the or method to set the gradient variant for the fill.
